Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Double-Slit Interference", "TechNoteSection",
 CellID->433762024,ExpressionUUID->"f8f7cfdf-dc7c-4d10-9553-d42a73bc0abe"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The phase coherence of quantum states can be seen best in interference \
experiments. The most popular interference experiment is the double-slit \
experiment in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 1",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#558165168"],
 " (a). Ranked top in a survey (Crease, 2002) about \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]the most beautiful experiment in physics,\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] the double-slit experiment with electrons (J\
\[ODoubleDot]nsson, 1961) played a decisive role to establish de Broglie\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s wave-particle duality for any particle in quantum \
physics. Notably, in a later experiment (Tonomura ",
 StyleBox["et al",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "., 1989), there was only one electron in the apparatus at any one time. \
This was one of the thought experiment that Feynman (Feynman ",
 StyleBox["et al",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "., 1963) suggested emphasizing the coherent nature of the quantum state. In \
Dirac\[CloseCurlyQuote]s words (Dirac, 1958), \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]each \
[electron] interferes only with itself.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1179529322,ExpressionUUID->"43bc1c4a-46d0-4320-a15f-6731845f87d1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Feynman\[CloseCurlyQuote]s other thought experiment (Feynman ",
 StyleBox["et al",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "., 1963) illustrated in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 1",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#558165168"],
 " (b) is an interesting variant of the double-slit experiment in the present \
context. In this experiment, a particle detector located at the upper slit \
can determine which slit each electron passes through. The so-called \
which-path information breaks the interference pattern and one can observe no \
interference fringe. A common explanation of the disappearance of \
interference in this experiment is based on the principle of complementarity. \
In quantum mechanics, anything has both the wave and particle nature but \
exhibits only one of them exclusively at a time (in a given situation). \
Indeed, the experiment is essentially the same as the thought experiment \
suggested by Einstein in a discussion with Bohr at the Fifth Physical \
Conference of the Solvay Institute, devoted to \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Electrons and Photons\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] (Bohr, \
1949), in 1927. Bohr gave the same argument. However, a closer analysis of \
the thought experiment also reveals the physical mechanism of decoherence. \
Here we will focus on this point."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1998887455,ExpressionUUID->"24d6e66c-dbd8-4ecf-b7e9-763718c185fc"],

