Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Partial Decoherence", "TechNoteSection",
 CellID->226170303,ExpressionUUID->"64c6f680-9ecc-4543-8a10-61d539636039"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In Feynman\[CloseCurlyQuote]s thought experiment in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 1",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#558165168"],
 " (b), it has been assumed that the particle detector behind the upper slit \
is perfect. In the Mach-Zehnder version in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 2",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#1995122200"],
 " (right), it corresponds to an interaction between the photon and the \
two-level system such that the quantum state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "1"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b7e67efb-84e2-486f-bc6e-f3ddb850945a"],
 " of the two-level system after the interaction is orthogonal to the initial \
state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2ea748a3-3c45-4b73-b1e2-e039a49128a3"],
 ". Recall that in principle one can devise a measurement to discriminate two \
orthogonal states with certainty."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1092516096,ExpressionUUID->"207e82aa-f3cf-4e4a-9d3f-5bdb97f5a80f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "What if the detector is not perfect? For example, suppose that the detector \
efficiency is so low that it often misses the particle even if it passes \
through the upper slit. How much would the presence of such a detector \
affect, if at all, the interference pattern in the screen? Translated to the \
Mach-Zehnder experiment in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 2",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#1995122200"],
 " (right), it corresponds to a quantum state, now denoted by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "1", "\[Prime]"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ce59379e-71d4-427a-9cf3-e819599d61f4"],
 " to be distinguished from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "1"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f5490699-bfcc-44d1-ac71-ec19fb7aecee"],
 ", of the two-level system after the interaction with the photon is not \
orthogonal to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "68179ec6-0f88-4c10-b20f-5b147db8b837"],
 ". It is also analogous to the quantum circuit in ",
 ButtonBox["Figure 4",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->
   "paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/HowQuantumDecoherenceOccurs#273364983"],
 ", where the unitary gate ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9827aff2-36c7-4f07-a652-96d873c5af30"],
 " is responsible for the transition ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"]},
     "Ket"], "\[RightArrow]", 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "1", "\[Prime]"]},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7b924c42-4a56-4528-9ab8-7f2276445bae"],
 ", that is, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "1", "\[Prime]"]},
     "Ket"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"U", 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "0"]},
      "Ket"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ba1418a3-5504-433c-95b6-7bdfd85389eb"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->336446689,ExpressionUUID->"b6d5e150-9871-4223-9f8f-d2103c2bb41e"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[
 GraphicsBox[{
   {Dashing[{Small, Small}], LineBox[{}]}, 
